{"parentUuid":"1c7aba68-44f3-42dc-a6b9-2a952ce14736","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a314bc97408580996","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011NxvnPMD36dKnhhShb1J1y","type":"tool_result","content":"123:system, optimizing matrix-multiplication kernels used to train LLMs, optimizing arithmetic\n302:  return hyper.zipit([...])                                               self._conv1 = hk.Conv2D(num_channels, kernel_shape=3)\n303:# EVOLVE-BLOCK-END                                                        self._conv2 = hk.Conv2D(num_channels * 2, kernel_shape=3)\n304:                                                                          self._conv3 = hk.Conv2D(num_channels * 4, kernel_shape=3)\n321:especially with weight decay.                                             self._conv1 = hk.Conv2D(num_channels, kernel_shape=3)\n1214:fused into the kernel, and low-level compiler intricacies, among other details.\n1217:3.3.2. Enhancing Gemini kernel engineering\n1220:specialized programs (kernels) tailored for optimal execution on hardware accelerators.\n1221:Therefore, efficient Pallas kernels are crucial for optimizing Gemini’s training performance.\n1222:A critical aspect of kernel optimization is tuning the tiling strategy for matrix multiplication\n1225:which is key to accelerating the overall computation. Traditionally, kernel engineers rely on\n1230:deep understanding of both kernel functionality and hardware intricacies. The key advantage\n1232:shapes. Consequently, to expedite the design of performant kernels for emerging hardware\n1236:important matrix multiplication kernel used to train Gemini. The objective is to minimize\n1237:the kernel’s actual runtime. AlphaEvolve iteratively explores and refines tiling heuristics for\n1238:this kernel by proposing candidate code, aiming to minimize this runtime on various input\n1239:shapes on real TPU accelerators. The kernel’s correctness is maintained by construction\n1240:because AlphaEvolve is optimizing the tiling strategy for this kernel rather than altering\n1249:AlphaEvolve, we automatically collect realistic kernel input shapes from kernel users. Half\n1254:average 23% kernel speedup across all kernels over the existing expert-designed heuristic,","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"0574f0c1-55f9-4c1e-a1bb-d1124cf333af","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:02.944Z","toolUseResult":{"stdout":"123:system, optimizing matrix-multiplication kernels used to train LLMs, optimizing arithmetic\n302:  return hyper.zipit([...])                                               self._conv1 = hk.Conv2D(num_channels, kernel_shape=3)\n303:# EVOLVE-BLOCK-END                                                        self._conv2 = hk.Conv2D(num_channels * 2, kernel_shape=3)\n304:                                                                          self._conv3 = hk.Conv2D(num_channels * 4, kernel_shape=3)\n321:especially with weight decay.                                             self._conv1 = hk.Conv2D(num_channels, kernel_shape=3)\n1214:fused into the kernel, and low-level compiler intricacies, among other details.\n1217:3.3.2. Enhancing Gemini kernel engineering\n1220:specialized programs (kernels) tailored for optimal execution on hardware accelerators.\n1221:Therefore, efficient Pallas kernels are crucial for optimizing Gemini’s training performance.\n1222:A critical aspect of kernel optimization is tuning the tiling strategy for matrix multiplication\n1225:which is key to accelerating the overall computation. Traditionally, kernel engineers rely on\n1230:deep understanding of both kernel functionality and hardware intricacies. The key advantage\n1232:shapes. Consequently, to expedite the design of performant kernels for emerging hardware\n1236:important matrix multiplication kernel used to train Gemini. The objective is to minimize\n1237:the kernel’s actual runtime. AlphaEvolve iteratively explores and refines tiling heuristics for\n1238:this kernel by proposing candidate code, aiming to minimize this runtime on various input\n1239:shapes on real TPU accelerators. The kernel’s correctness is maintained by construction\n1240:because AlphaEvolve is optimizing the tiling strategy for this kernel rather than altering\n1249:AlphaEvolve, we automatically collect realistic kernel input shapes from kernel users. Half\n1254:average 23% kernel speedup across all kernels over the existing expert-designed heuristic,","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1c7aba68-44f3-42dc-a6b9-2a952ce14736","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"0574f0c1-55f9-4c1e-a1bb-d1124cf333af","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a314bc97408580996","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011maVNN9vRDb5FJbvgJmyqA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything needed, including the precise characterization that AlphaEvolve optimizes kernels/tiling (training-infrastructure speed) — not the LLM's weights — and that distilling its outputs into the base model is only described as a future step. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Limitations / What It Cannot Do\n\nAll quotes below are verbatim. Two primary sources:\n- **White paper PDF** (DeepMind-hosted): `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` — also on arXiv as **2506.13131** (`https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.13131`, HTML mirror `https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2506.13131`).\n- **Blog post**: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n## Falsifiable claims with citations\n\n### 1. The main stated limitation: it requires an automated evaluator; problems needing manual experimentation are OUT OF SCOPE\nThis is DeepMind's single most explicit caveat, stated twice.\n\n- **White paper, §6 Discussion (the \"main limitation\" sentence), verbatim:**\n  > \"The main limitation of AlphaEvolve is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator. While this is true of many problems in the mathematical and computational sciences, there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\n  Source: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` (§6 Discussion, p. 20).\n\n- **White paper, early section (Section 2 / Table 1 discussion), verbatim:**\n  > \"While the use of an automated evaluation metric offers AlphaEvolve a key advantage, it is also a limitation—in particular, it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope. Because problems in mathematics, computer science, and system optimization typically permit automated evaluation metrics, our efforts on AlphaEvolve focus on these domains.\"\n  Source: same PDF (p. 3, around Table 1).\n\n### 2. Scope is defined as problems whose solution \"can be described as an algorithm, and automatically verified\"\n- **Blog post, verbatim:**\n  > \"While AlphaEvolve is currently being applied across math and computing, its general nature means it can be applied to any problem whose solution can be described as an algorithm, and automatically verified.\"\n  Source: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n- **Blog post**, on the necessity of automated metrics, verbatim:\n  > \"These metrics provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\"\n  Source: same blog URL.\n\n### 3. AlphaEvolve does NOT modify Gemini's weights — it improves *infrastructure / training kernels*, not the model itself\nDeepMind never claims it edits or retrains the base LLM's parameters. What it improved about the LLM pipeline is the **matrix-multiplication kernel tiling** used to *train* Gemini (a speed/throughput optimization), with correctness preserved by construction:\n\n- **White paper, §3.3.2 \"Enhancing Gemini kernel engineering,\" verbatim:**\n  > \"The kernel's correctness is maintained by construction because AlphaEvolve is optimizing the tiling strategy for this kernel rather than altering [the computation]…\"\n  > \"…average 23% kernel speedup across all kernels over the existing expert-designed heuristic…\"\n  Source: PDF §3.3.2 (p. 16–17).\n\n- The blog frames this as improving how Gemini is *trained/served*, not the weights:\n  > \"By finding smarter ways to divide a large matrix multiplication operation into more manageable subproblems, it sped up this vital kernel in Gemini's architecture by 23%, leading to a 1% reduction in Gemini's training time.\"\n  Source: blog URL above.\n\nThis supports the claim \"AlphaEvolve is not recursive self-improvement of the model itself.\" Corroborated by secondary analysis (Google Cloud Community / Medium): \"AlphaEvolve has improved the matrix multiplication kernel used to train the Gemini models… this is optimization of the training infrastructure and kernels, not direct improvement of the LLM's weights or core model parameters.\" Source: `https://medium.com/google-cloud/overcoming-llm-performance-plateau-alphaevolves-evolutionary-approach-to-continuous-gemini-e5a22c64b540`\n\n### 4. Improving the base LLM with AlphaEvolve's outputs is explicitly framed as FUTURE WORK (distillation), not something the system does\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"…a natural next step will be to consider distilling the AlphaEvolve-augmented performance of the base LLMs into the next generation of the base models. This can have intrinsic value and also, likely, uplift the next version of AlphaEvolve.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\n- And the self-improvement-of-infrastructure loop is described as **moderate and slow (months)**, verbatim:\n  > \"Beyond distillation, it is also intriguing that AlphaEvolve can make practical discoveries that increase the efficiency of its own infrastructure and of (future versions of) its base LLMs. Currently, the gains are moderate and the feedback loops for improving the next version of AlphaEvolve are on the order of months.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\nThis is the strongest verbatim DeepMind material against a \"fast recursive self-improvement / takeoff\" reading: the loop closes only via human-run future training generations, on a months-long cadence, with moderate gains.\n\n### 5. AlphaEvolve is positioned as a \"test-time compute agent\" enhancing the base LLM's *capability at inference*, not changing the model\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"AlphaEvolve can also be seen as a test-time compute agent that, through its evolutionary procedure, significantly enhances the capability of the base LLM (compared to, e.g., repeated sampling).\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\nThe enhancement is to *outputs via search at test time*, not to weights — reinforcing claims #3 and #4.\n\n### 6. LLM-as-judge evaluation is allowed but explicitly NOT optimized for — i.e. the system in practice depends on programmatic evaluators\n- **White paper §6, verbatim:**\n  > \"While AlphaEvolve does allow for LLM-provided evaluation of ideas, this is not a setting we have optimized for. However, concurrent work shows this is possible [34], and a natural step would be to link the two settings, with LLMs providing feedback on high-level ideas before transitioning to an implementation stage, for which machine feedback is available through code execution.\"\n  Source: PDF §6 (p. 20).\n\n### 7. Human-defined problems and metrics constrain autonomy (secondary framing of the same limitation)\nDeepMind's primary sources don't claim autonomy; secondary commentary makes the boundary explicit: AlphaEvolve \"cannot independently identify or define new challenges\" and \"relies on human-defined problems and evaluation metrics,\" restricting its autonomy. Sources: `https://www.unite.ai/alphaevolve-google-deepminds-groundbreaking-step-toward-agi/` and `https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/what-is-alphaevolve-google-ai-self-improvement-2`\n\n### 8. On the \"recursive self-improvement / AGI\" framing — contested, and DeepMind itself does not claim AGI\n- DeepMind's own materials make **no AGI claim** and **no recursive-self-improvement claim**; the closest is the cautious \"increase the efficiency of its own infrastructure… gains are moderate… feedback loops… on the order of months\" (claim #4).\n- Secondary coverage frames it at most as a \"careful/measured\" early form of recursive self-improvement and \"a step toward AGI,\" not AGI itself. Sources: `https://www.unite.ai/alphaevolve-google-deepminds-groundbreaking-step-toward-agi/`, `https://www.geeky-gadgets.com/alpha-evolve-ai-recursive-learning/`\n\n## Notes on sourcing\n- The white-paper page numbers above are from the DeepMind-hosted PDF; the identical text is in arXiv 2506.13131 (§6 \"Discussion\" and the Section 2 paragraph following Table 1).\n- I could not surface dedicated AlphaEvolve limitations coverage from MIT Tech Review / Ars Technica / IEEE Spectrum in the available US search results; the strongest expert-limitation framing came directly from DeepMind's own §6 Discussion plus unite.ai, HPCwire/AIwire (`https://www.hpcwire.com/2025/06/02/can-alphaevolve-change-how-we-solve-problems-a-look-inside-deepminds-latest-breakthrough/`), and the Google Cloud Community write-up. The primary-source quotes (claims #1–#6) are the load-bearing, verbatim, falsifiable ones."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1006,"cache_read_input_tokens":23098,"output_tokens":3261,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1006},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3261,"cache_read_input_tokens":23098,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1006,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1006,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG29nHuLsdYSzdvY719U","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"070689c0-b619-4287-bc78-5bd8527f465d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:43.421Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
